00:00:25.380 --> 00:00:29.340
to welcome Brazilian author, Noemi
Jaffe, to the library of Congress.

00:00:29.340 --> 00:00:32.130
We just had a session recording for
the Archives of Hispanic Literature

00:00:32.130 --> 00:00:34.150
on tape, and it was amazing.

00:00:34.150 --> 00:00:39.250 position:56%
So please look forward to
listening to her read from her work.

00:00:39.250 --> 00:00:43.300
Noemi Jaffe taught
Brazilian literature full-time

00:00:43.300 --> 00:00:46.580
for over 20 years, and then
one day decided I'm going

00:00:46.580 --> 00:00:51.390
to be a full-time writer, which
is what she does currently,

00:00:51.390 --> 00:00:56.810
besides teaching creative
writing in Brazil, as well.

00:00:56.810 --> 00:01:00.220
She's a frequent contributor
to the Cultural Supplement

00:01:00.220 --> 00:01:03.610
of the [Portuguese name] and
also writes a monthly column

00:01:03.610 --> 00:01:04.910
for the newspaper [Portuguese name]

00:01:04.910 --> 00:01:08.690
and for the magazine,
Harper's Bazaar.

00:01:08.690 --> 00:01:13.130
She's the author of 10 titles,
starting with her book of poetry,

00:01:13.130 --> 00:01:16.100
which was also her first
book published, right?

00:01:16.100 --> 00:01:22.100
[Portuguese name], All the
Little Things, published in 2005.

00:01:22.100 --> 00:01:26.610
In 2016, she received
the Brazil Literary Prize

00:01:26.610 --> 00:01:30.880
for her novel [Portuguese
name] The Orchids.

00:01:30.880 --> 00:01:33.270
Today, she will be
reading and talking

00:01:33.270 --> 00:01:38.550 position:56%
about her recently translated novel
[Portuguese name] What are the Blind

00:01:38.550 --> 00:01:40.030
Men Dreaming?

00:01:40.030 --> 00:01:43.380
Which was a finalist for the prize
[Portuguese name] Literary Prize

00:01:43.380 --> 00:01:44.680
