00:04:00.250 --> 00:04:03.230
&gt;&gt; Noemi Jaffe: Okay
well first of all,

00:04:03.230 --> 00:04:08.860
I'd also like to think the Library
of Congress for inviting me,

00:04:08.860 --> 00:04:14.640 position:56%
Talia and Vivaldo, and I'd also like
to say how excited I am to be here.

00:04:14.640 --> 00:04:17.410
It's a dream of mine
to come to the library,

00:04:17.410 --> 00:04:22.070 position:56%
imagine even talking in the library.

00:04:22.070 --> 00:04:24.540
So I'm very excited.

00:04:24.540 --> 00:04:27.240
And good. Well, to
answer your question,

00:04:27.240 --> 00:04:30.430
it's a question everybody
wants to know, right?

00:04:30.430 --> 00:04:34.570 position:56%
Because the title is pretty strange.

00:04:34.570 --> 00:04:37.160
Well, my mother is a
very curious person.

00:04:37.160 --> 00:04:44.670
She's always wondering about
phenomenon, natural phenomenon,

00:04:44.670 --> 00:04:48.490
about cosmic phenomenons,
and she usually calls me

00:04:48.490 --> 00:04:57.460
or asks me questions about natural
things like why is the world round?

00:04:57.460 --> 00:05:00.220
And why do dogs bark?

00:05:00.220 --> 00:05:05.370
And while I was writing the book,
she called me one day and asked me,

00:05:05.370 --> 00:05:08.870
"Noemi, what are the
blind men dreaming?"

00:05:08.870 --> 00:05:14.370
And the question was so --
it came just out of the blue,

00:05:14.370 --> 00:05:18.900
it was so poetic, that I
didn't know how to answer her,

00:05:18.900 --> 00:05:21.690
but I immediately said,
mom, that's the title

00:05:21.690 --> 00:05:26.000 position:56%
of the book, and she agreed with me.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:29.260
She was wondering what
blind men dream of,

00:05:29.260 --> 00:05:35.670
because his blind men don't see,
she was thinking how do they dream

00:05:35.670 --> 00:05:37.990
if they don't see, right?

00:05:37.990 --> 00:05:42.200
But she has this problem
in her Brazilian grammar.

00:05:42.200 --> 00:05:45.350
She hasn't learned Brazilian
grammar very well, and so instead

00:05:45.350 --> 00:05:49.130
of asking what do blind
men dream of, she asked,

00:05:49.130 --> 00:05:53.770
"What are the blind men dreaming?"

00:05:53.770 --> 00:06:01.370
And I like this mistake, quotes,
because it somehow talks a lot

00:06:01.370 --> 00:06:03.650
about herself, the way she lives.

00:06:03.650 --> 00:06:05.760
She lives in the present
continuously.

00:06:05.760 --> 00:06:08.130
That's her decision.

00:06:08.130 --> 00:06:12.770
That in order to survive
what she went through,

00:06:12.770 --> 00:06:16.700
because she is a survivor
from Auschwitz,

00:06:16.700 --> 00:06:19.690
she decided to forget
everything that happened to her.

00:06:19.690 --> 00:06:23.090
So she's always living
in the present tense,

00:06:23.090 --> 00:06:26.510
and the present continues
to be more specific.

00:06:26.510 --> 00:06:35.730
So in the first place, I
thought it was very compatible,

00:06:35.730 --> 00:06:37.030
very convenient.

00:06:37.030 --> 00:06:41.240
The present continuous was
the best tense for her.

00:06:41.240 --> 00:06:42.840
So what are the blind men dreaming?

00:06:42.840 --> 00:06:47.410
And also, the content of the
question was also perfect,

00:06:47.410 --> 00:06:57.140
because it talks about her
imagination, about her curiosity,

00:06:57.140 --> 00:07:01.810
and also, it describes the
blindness, both of the people

00:07:01.810 --> 00:07:06.050
who are inside the camp, and who
are forbidden to dream, right?

00:07:06.050 --> 00:07:07.750
Because when you're suffering

00:07:07.750 --> 00:07:13.130 position:56%
as people do inside a concentration
camp, how can you dream of anything?

00:07:13.130 --> 00:07:18.000 position:56%
And also because they didn't know
what was happening outside the camp,

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:20.150 position:56%
what was happening the world, right?

00:07:20.150 --> 00:07:23.490
And also, because the
people outside the camp,

00:07:23.490 --> 00:07:27.410
both the ones who did know
what was going on inside it,

00:07:27.410 --> 00:07:29.600
but didn't do anything, right?

00:07:29.600 --> 00:07:33.040
Because people who work
in the city of Auschwitz,

00:07:33.040 --> 00:07:38.970
they were feeling the smell
of burning flesh all day long,

00:07:38.970 --> 00:07:40.270
and they didn't do anything.

00:07:40.270 --> 00:07:44.380
Not even go to the
border of the camp to see

00:07:44.380 --> 00:07:48.350
if people needed a
piece of bread, nothing.

00:07:48.350 --> 00:07:51.510
And also, the people who
didn't know what was happening,

00:07:51.510 --> 00:07:56.290
because Germany tried to
disguise it is much as they could.

00:07:56.290 --> 00:08:00.130
And I think the third reason is

00:08:00.130 --> 00:08:03.210
because I think people
are still blind

00:08:03.210 --> 00:08:05.490
to what's happening
in the world, right?

00:08:05.490 --> 00:08:09.560
Because there are happening things
that are similar to what happened

00:08:09.560 --> 00:08:12.370
in Auschwitz, and we're
still blind to it.

00:08:12.370 --> 00:08:14.650
We're not doing much.

00:08:14.650 --> 00:08:18.330
And so that's the reason
for the title of the book.

00:08:18.330 --> 00:08:19.660
And there are other reasons.

00:08:19.660 --> 00:08:23.340
People always come up
with different reasons.

00:08:23.340 --> 00:08:26.060
&gt;&gt; Vivaldo dos Santos: And thank
you, that was following up.

00:08:26.060 --> 00:08:29.770
I was thinking about also
