00:10:21.830 --> 00:10:25.350
why did you write this
diary if you don't write?

00:10:25.350 --> 00:10:28.130
And she said, "For you to read it."

00:10:28.130 --> 00:10:30.630
And she was 19 years
old at the time.

00:10:30.630 --> 00:10:34.290
She couldn't even imagine
she would have children,

00:10:34.290 --> 00:10:38.260
that she would meet my father,
and that she would come to Brazil.

00:10:38.260 --> 00:10:44.670
But anyway, and so I think
that for her to write,

00:10:44.670 --> 00:10:47.650
which is something she
wasn't used to doing.

00:10:47.650 --> 00:10:50.300
Like when she wants
to write a letter,

00:10:50.300 --> 00:10:54.410
we don't write letters anymore, but
when she wanted to write a letter,

00:10:54.410 --> 00:10:57.590
because her brother was living
here in the United States,

00:10:57.590 --> 00:11:01.240
she couldn't write more
than two lines like, "Hello.

00:11:01.240 --> 00:11:02.540
I'm in good health.

00:11:02.540 --> 00:11:03.840
So is my family.

00:11:03.840 --> 00:11:06.840
Goodbye." So she always
asked me, "Please,

00:11:06.840 --> 00:11:09.810
could you write a letter
for my brother?"

00:11:09.810 --> 00:11:11.110
She couldn't write.

00:11:11.110 --> 00:11:17.340
So I think that for her, it
actually was a kind of decision.

00:11:17.340 --> 00:11:21.920
I interpret that now, a
kind of decision of hers

00:11:21.920 --> 00:11:29.350
to extract her memory of what
had happened and leave it

00:11:29.350 --> 00:11:33.110
in a diary, so she could forget it.

00:11:33.110 --> 00:11:34.990
Because that's what she did.

00:11:34.990 --> 00:11:37.740
So all of her memories
are in that diary.

00:11:37.740 --> 00:11:40.840
She doesn't remember
anything different

00:11:40.840 --> 00:11:42.730
